The following definitions also apply:
* âenergy from renewable sourcesâ means energy from renewÂ­able non-fossil sources, namely wind, solar, aerothermal, geothermal, hydrothermal and ocean energy, hydropower, biomass, landfill gas, sewage treatment plant gas and biogases;
* âaerothermal energyâ means energy stored in the form of heat in the ambient air;
* âgeothermal energyâ means energy stored in the form of heat beneath the surface of solid earth;
* âhydrothermal energyâ means energy stored in the form of heat in surface water;
* âbiomassâ means the biodegradable fraction of products, waste and residues from biological origin from agriculture (including vegetal and animal substances), forestry and related industries including fisheries and aquaculture, as well as the biodegradable fraction of industrial and municipal waste;
* âgross final consumption of energyâ means the energy comÂ­modities delivered for energy purposes to industry, transport, households, services including public services, agriculture, forestry and fisheries, including the consumption of electricÂ­ity and heat by the energy branch for electricity and heat proÂ­duction and including losses of electricity and heat in distribution and transmission;
* âdistrict heatingâ or âdistrict coolingâ means the distribution of thermal energy in the form of steam, hot water or chilled liqÂ­uids, from a central source of production through a network to multiple buildings or sites, for the use of space or process heating or cooling;
* âbioliquidsâ means liquid fuel for energy purposes other than for transport, including electricity and heating and cooling, produced from biomass;
* âbiofuelsâ means liquid or gaseous fuel for transport produced from biomass;
* âguarantee of originâ means an electronic document which has the sole function of providing proof to a final customer that a given share or quantity of energy was produced from renewable sources as required by Article 3(6) of Directive 2003/54/EC;
* âsupport schemeâ means any instrument, scheme or mechaÂ­nism applied by a Member State or a group of Member States, that promotes the use of energy from renewable sources by reducing the cost of that energy, increasing the price at which it can be sold, or increasing, by means of a renewable energy obligation or otherwise, the volume of such energy purÂ­chased. This includes, but is not restricted to, investment aid, tax exemptions or reductions, tax refunds, renewable energy obligation support schemes including those using green cerÂ­tificates, and direct price support schemes including feed-in tariffs and premium payments;
* ârenewable energy obligationâ means a national support scheme requiring energy producers to include a given proÂ­portion of energy from renewable sources in their producÂ­tion, requiring energy suppliers to include a given proportion of energy from renewable sources in their supply, or requirÂ­ing energy consumers to include a given proportion of energy from renewable sources in their consumption. This includes schemes under which such requirements may be fulÂ­filled by using green certificates;
* âactual valueâ means the greenhouse gas emission saving for some or all of the steps of a specific biofuel production proÂ­cess calculated in accordance with the methodology laid down in part C of AnnexÂ V;
* âtypical valueâ means an estimate of the representative greenÂ­house gas emission saving for a particular biofuel production pathway;
* âdefault valueâ means a value derived from a typical value by the application of pre-determined factors and that may, in circumstances specified in this Directive, be used in place of an actual value.

For the purposes of this paragraph, the following provisions shall apply:
* for the calculation of the denominator, that is the total amount of energy consumed in transport for the purposes of the first subparagraph, only petrol, diesel, biofuels consumed in road and rail transport, and electricity shall be taken into account;
* for the calculation of the numerator, that is the amount of energy from renewable sources consumed in transport for the purposes of the first subparagraph, all types of energy from renewable sources consumed in all forms of transport shall be taken into account;
* for the calculation of the contribution from electricity proÂ­duced from renewable sources and consumed in all types of electric vehicles for the purpose of pointsÂ (a) andÂ (b), MemÂ­ber States may choose to use either the average share of elecÂ­tricity from renewable energy sources in the Community or
* for the calculation of the contribution from electricity proÂ­duced from renewable sources and consumed in all types of electric vehicles for the purpose of pointsÂ (a) andÂ (b), MemÂ­ber States may choose to use either the average share of elecÂ­tricity from renewable energy sources in the Community or
 the share of electricity from renewable energy sources in their own country as measured two years before the year in quesÂ­tion. Furthermore, for the calculation of the electricity from renewable energy sources consumed by electric road vehicles, that consumption shall be considered to be 2,5 times the energy content of the input of electricity from renewable energy sources.

For the purposes of measuring target compliance with the requirements of this Directive concerning national overall targets, the amount of electricity or heating or cooling from renewable energy sources notified in accordance with paragraph 1(b) shall be:
* deducted from the amount of electricity or heating or coolÂ­ing from renewable energy sources that is taken into account, in measuring compliance by the Member State issuing the letÂ­ter of notification under paragraphÂ 1; and
* added to the amount of electricity or heating or cooling from renewable energy sources that is taken into account, in meaÂ­suring compliance by the Member State receiving the letter of notification in accordance with paragraphÂ 2.
